Title: Reco Day
WorkoutDescription: In the pro cycling world Monday is considered the 'international day of rest'. Your body will be working hard nearly every other day of the week with bike and 'off bike' life. 1 day/ week to allow the body to rebuild, recoup from the stress that has been placed on it increases the effectiveness of the training. Also can be refreshing for the mind and motivation to allow yourself at least 1day/week away from the bike.

Title: CORE strength ON the bike.
WorkoutDescription: This is an interesting one. Can keep both feet clipped in for the whole ride this time. But something different thrown in there, an old trick from the Australian Institute of Sport, it's simple but VERY effective. For the 2 minute working efforts this time you are allowed to touch the handlebars with your FINGERTIPS ONLY. This engages your core/ stabilising muscles, you'll feel it! Be cogniscent of your upper body, you want to try to keep relatively still in these efforts, no swaying side to side. Imagine there is a spirit level across your shoulder blades. Focus your energy to your core & legs, that's where the bike wants it! I used to find these very satisfying and an easy way to engage more of the body than just the legs which is very important for getting as much power into those pedals as possible..
CoachComments: 15min: increasing intensity warm up. You should have some sweat dripping down by the end of this and have the Heart Rate pumping so you feel like you're about ready to smash some efforts. 25min: 5x 2min 7/10- 3min 2/10. ALL 7RPE efforts must be FINGERTIPS ONLY touching the handlebars. 10min: 7RPE, this is a good way to make the most of this workout, after those fingertip efforts you should be tired but find 10min of power to push through and sweat it out to the warm down. Put as much gas down as you like here.. Feel that core a little more engaged! 10min: warm down 2/10. Keep the cadence nice and high in the cool down (90+rpm)..
AthleteComments: *22/02/2022 Matthew Roberts: I was genuinely pedallig at 4 RPE but my HR was much higher than I expected based on leg feel.  I suppose engaging the extra muscles does that?  Wasn't able to hold my form for teh 10 min interval.  Kept to fingertips but was sitting up, resting on a leg, etc.* *22/02/2022 Matthew Roberts: A wet quarter sessions rd is not long enough for a 10 min effort!  I only got an hour between storms, so it was the best I could do.* *24/02/2022 Justin Morris: Glad you got out mate. Hats off to ya for braving the elements. The high HR can result from a number of things: - the novelty of an effort - humidity - freshness - coming down with a virus.. So think it likely the first 3 of those for you. Kind of good to know the legs were only at 4RPE. Means your strength is good. Just the cardio that will help from here. Anyway, first session done. Nice work Matt!*

Title: SPIN to WIN!
WorkoutDescription: This could be done outside on a flat road. A cadence counter will be a big benefit here this measures how fast your pedals spin around (in RPM). If you do not have one of these feel the sensation of spinning those legs in the easiest gear possible.. This is the sensation you want to aim for in most of this workout. A fast, consistent cadence (leg speed) is a crucial key to unlocking power, efficiency and form on the bike. Have a look at a professional cyclist in a race. Not the speed of the legs turning around it is fast, not so much grinding but spinning! When you spin as opposed to 'grind' the pedals you sustain the energy in your muscles for longer and you end up getting more power into the pedals. A high cadence also activates more of your cardio system so you are getting a very comprehensive fitness/ weight loss workout. Grinding a hard gear you activate the strength/ aerobic system which would be similar to going to the gym and doing leg press/ squats. Note the higher leg speed in the working sections, this should help spike your heart rate and ensure not only a good development of form/ style but also a full gas cardio workout! SPIN to WIN!!
CoachComments: 10min: Z1- 4/10 Perceived Rate of Exhaustion. 15min: Z2- 7/10 PRE 10min: Z1- 5/10 15min: Z2- 7/10 little harder than first effort. 10min: Z1- 4/10 cool down.
AthleteComments: *23/02/2022 Matthew Roberts: Spinning is not my forte!  Right knee (which sometimes give me grief) was not happy on first interval but better on second.  I think it was my poor form, which did improve.  It genuinely takes all my brain power to keep a high cadence.  Changing gears every second because any up or down slope puts you out of the range.  beyond 105rpm and I can't keep good form.  I cannot spin fast without some pressure on the pedals either.  If I want to keep spinning easily on a down slope when the bike is speeding up, my pedal stroke goes super lumpy and it feels terrible.  Still, got it done.* *24/02/2022 Justin Morris: Yeah, thats normal when doing this outside. Your feedback there is pretty normal for outside spinning on lumpy terrain. Rest assured you will still get benefit from it. Good to teach yourself to spin the legs even on the downhills too. It may feel clunky etc but it is still serving a purpose in flushing lactic out of the legs.*

Title: Building Blocks
WorkoutDescription: This is what we use to grow extend threshold, burn fat and increase cardio capacity. It may seem boring but play some music/ podcast from your ipod or whatever. This stuff is BOSS. What turns you into a cyclist.. Aim for the RPE/ data numbers. But CADENCE is important if you have a cadence counter aim for an average of 90 or above.. If not just spin those legs as fast as you can.. Most importantly in the recovery periods as this is what flushes the toxins out of those legs muscles and helps them to recover so they are ready to smash the pedals again!
CoachComments: These long efforts are the gospel of high performance cycling, this is ensuring your 'base' is nice and strong, this is your foundation for building strength and speed upon. Without a nice, solid BASE nothing else is sustained.
AthleteComments: *24/02/2022 Matthew Roberts: had to manually adjust since I forgot to stop the wahoo when I got home.  Struggled to keep up the effort on the final interval, legs just wouldn't push.  Quads full of fatigue.  Spent too much brain power trying to keep the cadence up and didn't hit the efforts as close as I would like.* *24/02/2022 Justin Morris: Bit of carry over from yesterdays one. Pretty glad you were able to get out all 3days so far this week Matt. The duration is one of the biggest benefits in this one, soon will have some precise HR zones for you. looking at this you did pretty good though, can see the dip in final effort but covered some good ground!*

Title: 90min HARD on MTB
WorkoutDescription: Can be MTB ON ROAD if the trails are sodden. Just want you to prepare for going hard in this position. Saving for the first and last 10min, keep HR 145bpm+. So about a 7.5/10 and above.

Title: Flat Foot strength
WorkoutDescription: This may seem counter intuitive after the 'Spin to win' fest. But today we are slowing that RPM right down to emphasise the importance of the position of your foot in the pedal action. Note in those 6minute 'working' sectors the cadence range is slowed right down to 50-60. I want you pushing a hard gear and being cognisant of that 'sccoping' motion through the pedal stroke. Imagine you are taking a spoonful of neopolitan and the sole of your shoe is the spoon. During this entire pedal stroke focus on keeping the sole of that foot PARALLEL to the floor during the whole motion. The flatter that foot is the more power goes into those pedals.. Again channel all that energy from the mind, forehead, neck, shoulders... ALL the way down your body and into those pedals. This will activate your strength system which is important especially for hill climbing and sprinting. Note the RPM numbers and keep that foot flat! Another habit we are trying to create with this workout.
CoachComments: The 6 min 10/10 sections I just want you seated in the drops pushing HARD gear as possible with cadence only 60rpm!
AthleteComments: *02/03/2022 Matthew Roberts: This type of thing is right up my alley.  No problems grinding a low gear and form seemed OK from the start (as far as I can tell)* *03/03/2022 Justin Morris: Good man, yep gathered you'd like these ones after our chat. These translate into increase in climbing power. So be good to keep a good rhythm of these going, they not the type of effort where you notice quick big gains. More of a gradual development but takes you high in the power output/ endurance. generally a 10-12 week consistent use of these style efforts really lifts a rider.*

Title: Home Trainer 1 Leg Session !
WorkoutDescription: This is designed to SMOOTH out your pedalling motion. It is very, very effective but also quite challenging! Set up a chair or something to prop your non working leg on next to the trainer. The main priority in this is to be SMOOTH! No stress about heart rate or power or anything else. Smooth, like you are buttering toast with peanut butter and the bottom of your foot is the knife. I don't want you to stress about numbers per se. The 9 & 6 RPE on the workout builder are just to indicate when the 1 leg sessions are (9=1 leg, 6+2 legs). NO power, NO HR really required The 1 minute between each 1 leg sector allows a bit of recovery (clip both legs back in for this 1 min). Then that 10min working session toward the end both legs in and I want you to note if you feel any different sensations in your pedal stroke after doing the 1 leggers Another KEY building block for a cyclist, this is FORM and STYLE on the bike - this is what allows you to push more power through the pedals when we dial this in.
CoachComments: This will give you 4x1 min Left leg and 4x 1min Right leg. Nice and even!
AthleteComments: *02/03/2022 Matthew Roberts: Ouch!.  My thighs did not like that.  I could feel that in my thighs way before any other part of me was working hard.  Found a better spot for my resting leg eventually that made things a bit better but that was tough.* *03/03/2022 Justin Morris: Hard to back these up from yesterday as similar targets. Often overlooked the fluidity of the pedal stroke but really helps lift ya.*

Title: COLD shower
WorkoutDescription: Last 30seconds of your shower needs to be COLD!!
CoachComments: This is old school but has sooo many benefits both mentally and physically. It gives the body a short taste of hot/cold treatment which the AIS uses for muscle recovery after hard sessions. It also helps the immune system, symapthetic and parasympathetic nervous system. Most importantly though it introduces another just small element of pain tolerance into the day..
AthleteComments: *05/03/2022 Matthew Roberts: not fun*

Title: Trainer- FOCUS training
WorkoutDescription: After getting the blood pumping for 10min or so, I want you to engage the mind in turning those pedals...- Do this by COUNTING EACH PEDAL STROKE! See how high of a number you can get. If your mind wanders and you lose count... Start again!! 1 rotation of the pedals= 1 count! Continue for 10mins then 5min break where mind can wander again, then 10mins ON with the counting again. The RPE denotes 'mental power' in this session as opposed to leg power..
CoachComments: The idea of this is to FOCUS 100% of your thinking power to turning the pedals. The rationale is that if your mind is not fully engaged you cannot be giving your full potential of energy to the practice. COMPLETELY PRESENT!! The counting is the most straightforward way to train the mind toward 100% focus on what you are doing.. No thinking about work, no thinking about whats for brekkie, no thinking about the future or the past- JUST turning the pedals. Somewhat like meditation!
AthleteComments: *03/03/2022 Matthew Roberts: Thighs still sore from yesterday but they loosened up. Still constant rain here. 955 was the highest I counted to ;)*

Title: Brew ride/ Active recovery MTB OR Road bike
WorkoutDescription: Good day to get on the bike still but without the stress/ structure of a working session. Important to turn the legs over today but no need to smash any efforts or drills. Aim to keep leg speed (cadence) HIGH and heart rate LOW.
CoachComments: Great opportunity for a friendly coffee shop ride.
AthleteComments: *05/03/2022 Matthew Roberts: legs felt stiff when I got up this morning, but felt fine on the ride.* *05/03/2022 Matthew Roberts: spinning at 90rpm+ never feels easy, so I don't normally do that on a recovery ride, but it seemed to work out just fine.*

Title: 'buddhism efforts'
WorkoutDescription: This best done outside on road bike. The idea is to train your mind to be 100% IN THE MOMENT of the effort you are doing.. Squeeze, the most out of the effort you can. The key is to eliminate thoughts before they get into your mind during the effort. Here we want JUST REACTIONS NO thinking!! COMPLETELY IN the effort physically and mentally.. These longer efforts around 7-8RPE are again working on that base load and pushing your threshold higher. Hitting that 8RPE puts you into the 'hurt bag' here you are suffering, not able to talk at all.. Pushes the body and brain further into being present.
CoachComments: I like these as helps remind us of where we are in this moment, in this point of time!! Can be very beneficial for cycling and for life!
AthleteComments: *06/03/2022 Matthew Roberts: Had to hide from the rain half way through. 2 hours without a downpour is too much to ask it seems. Spun my legs much faster in the efforts and that helped keep them up as I got tired.* *07/03/2022 Justin Morris: Awesome grit being shown riding in the rain Matt. Another good session which would have been hard today after the week you have put out. HR still beating well which is good to know after a hard week. Quick adaptation!*

Title: FTHR test
WorkoutDescription: Wear HR strap.The aim of this is to help ascertain some of the important HR values required from your power/HR data. This is called your 'functional threshold' test. It gives us a number that indicates how hard you can go for approximately an hour. Suggestion: Hornsby side Bobbin Head or any hill that goes for 20min or has flat over the top rather than a descent. Pony club could be good too if you keep pushing over toward the school and then up Bellamy until you hit the 20min mark.
CoachComments: I would suggest a long, flat road with 0 traffic lights/ distractions. Pay attention to the 3 high leg speed warm up drills prior to the effort, these are important to get the mosyt out of this effort. The effort will 20mins FLAT OUT! Imagine you are doing a time trial, focus your attention, your energy, your thoughts on the effort. This will encourage you to look inside your feeling a little and help you appreicate how hard you can actually go and how much pain you can actually deal with!
AthleteComments: *10/03/2022 Justin Morris: GREAT work mate! Solid number for the home trainer too. A solid 20min blast was awesome. Now we have some HR data to work with :-)!! Will get even more exciting :-).*

Title: OUT of the saddle efforts
WorkoutDescription: This is especially important if racing is ever on your radar. learning to SPRINT full gas on the bike and get as much power/ purpose into those pedals as possible. Those 30second efforts with only 30seconds recovery afterward are going to HURT! This is where you learn how that pain cave feels.. After this you'll know you can survive in that pain cave and know you can hop in there again when need be. When sprinting out of the saddle keeping that upper body steady becomes even more important. Remember you're not in a rodeo on the back of a bucking bronco here. You want to get as much power into those pedals as you can.. From everything you've learnt already, steady upper body, flat feet, deep composed breathing, high cadence these drills are just smacking all of that learning and packaging into only 30seconds.
CoachComments: FULL GAS sprints, you want be in the drops for the sprints to maximise aerodynamics, on the hoods for reco to open up the shoulders and get more air in.
AthleteComments: *10/03/2022 Matthew Roberts: First round I was all over the place. Much better form in the second round but maybe I could have gone harder.* *10/03/2022 Justin Morris: Form is important on these ones. Good to refine, this will become a bigger part of your plan a bit further down the track. They are much more efficient after having built a good block of strength foundation.*

WorkoutDescription: 4 seconds: breathe in through nose 4 seconds: hold breath 4 seconds: long breath out through mouth

Title: This good on the trainer- so maybe move to a wet day- Form, Strength & Cardio!
WorkoutDescription: This will be a full on session. The 1 leg is probably the most important part. Focus on being SMOOTH with your leg. Imagine you are scooping ice cream with your foot, pushing down AND pulling up making an effort to focus on form. SMOOTHness is what we are training here and streength. Try to have just a small snack (banana or something) before the session, eat every 30min during (bar/gel) and then have breakfast within 20min of finishing a good high carb/ protein meal. This is an awesome workout! I am excited even writing it. This is a good one!
CoachComments: -: Z1 warm up. 10min: Z2 build the power and HR up so you are sweating and reaching a moderate level of discomfort. -: 1min ON, 3 min OFF. *KEY part*- The 1 minute WORKING portion has to be done with 1 LEG ONLY. Alternate on each working session. So you will have Left leg effort, right leg effort, left, right the 3min easy in between is both legs clipped in easy pedalling. Your cadence will drop significantly which is ok. FOCUS on form! Each set will get smoother! Main thing here is form, try to keep power and HR high, but focus on being smooth is more important. Be cogniscent of 'pedalling with the heel'. 10min: Z2, back to going steady hard session building up sweat. -: Repeat previous 4 sets of 1 leg efforts. 15min: Z1 cool down, chill. Ready for a day in the office:-).
AthleteComments: *16/03/2022 Matthew Roberts: Wet day so I moved this forward. Overalll felt easy but my thighs almost packed it in towards the end of the last few one legged intervals* *17/03/2022 Justin Morris: Good to hear, that means you were doing em properly :-). Such good strength workout, really cool to see you backing up on Thursday with the breathing session too.*

Title: Lollipop Efforts
WorkoutDescription: You will need a bag of Chupa Chups for this one! Breathing is the basis of performance in sport and indeed the basis of life. Getting it under control unlocks power/ energy that can contribute to your performance. The default habit when your HR is working is to suck in air via open mouth breathing. To begin to incorporate the passages of the nose will create a new habit that lends itself to increased performance. Breathing in through the nose generally gets a deeper breath than via the mouth also. Complete the warm up as per normal then at the 18-20min mark put the lollipop in the mouth and complete all extra efforts with the chupa chup in the mouth! An old school breath training technique that works! Be patient with it, try to let frustration pass over you during this. You are strong, like porcelain! 100% FOCUS on your effort with most of that focus being on your breath!
CoachComments: Have a spare lollipop or 3 on hand for when the first one runs out. Can be outside OR trainer.
AthleteComments: *17/03/2022 Matthew Roberts: I was very apprehensive when I saw the profile (ramp at the end?) but I felt really good. Hard work but went well. Breathing was no problem at all.* *17/03/2022 Justin Morris: Nice work Matt!! Yeah, the main thing with this one is the breathing focus, the ramp effort is hard enough without the lollipop focus. Glad to hear you found it ok. You must have a strong diaphragm!!*

Title: Climbing & Descending skills
WorkoutDescription: You'll need your local climb today and we are going to head UP and DOWN it 3 times with increasing intensity. ON THE CLIMB: Focus on keeping that upper body nice and relaxed and stable. Imagine your spone and the seatpost of your bike are one vertical line.. Aim for symmetry between your upper body and your machine. Relax those shoulders, deep breaths this will set off a wave of composure down your body. Turn it into power when it gets to your legs. Shift your weight slightly back in the saddle and encourage a 'scooping' motion through the pedals. Remember you are getting power into those pedals when pushing down AND when pulling up. Look at that RPE number and remember you want to SUSTAIn that effort for the entire climb. Don't go too deep at the bottom of the 1st climb.. ON THE DESCENT: Descending is an element in cycling where the gains can be easily made but the consequences of getting it wrong are often dire. Getting your mind comfortable and confident with the experience is often the most difficult part. On shallow descents where the gradient is not too steep and not too many corners focus on continuing to turn the legs over even if it may seem there is no power going into the pedals. This sustains the blood pumping through the legs and helps distribute your balance. Braking is important for more technical descents with corners, on the first descent be apprehensive and get to know the feel of the braking as you come INTO the corner. Try to avoid breaking in the corner. Your goal is to hit the corner already at an appropriate speed and avoiding having to hit the brakes as you turn. Similar to driving a car/ motorbike. You'll notice most of the steering on a descent does not come from the handlebars it comes from the distribution of your weight. Get this right and it assures you balance no matter how steep the road or sharp the turn. When turning, be attentive to counter steering. Balance the bike at speed by placing slight pressure on the handlebar on the opposing side to the direction of the corner. ie. For a left hand turn lean the bike left and keep pressure through the right hand onto the bars. This helps balance the machine when it is being lent over. Same with the feet, for right hand turn your left fott should be slammed down to the bottom of the pedal stroke and vice versa. Focus your attention to all these things and after 3 repeats you'll be on your way to making them new cycling habits.
CoachComments: 1st climb: Sub threshold 2nd climb: on threshold 3rd climb: Above threshold Then a 20min working session.

On trainer is fine if wet, otherwise roadie on the old highway heading north would work well. After warm up we have some longer 6min efforts, then some 40sec sprints, then a solid 20min effort (mid race pace) before building up again to a fast finish.

Title: Pre breakfast spin
WorkoutDescription: This is hard also I know but a great idea if you do get the right amount of sleep (7hrs or more). If you can set the alarm early and just hop on the trainer even just for 15-20min.. Easy spinning.. Just enough to break sweat. This is an old school pro cycling technique used to lose weight. The idea is that as soon as you wake up if you exercise right away before brekkie you are burning away at the ,latent energy in your body, not the food you've just consumed.
CoachComments: If you make this a habit just once or twice a week you should notice the benefits. Adequate rest the night before is key though.
AthleteComments: *02/04/2022 Matthew Roberts: I’ll do an hour today and an hour tomorrow instead of trying to do 2hrs on the trainer. Want to bank some training as well in case I go down*

Title: General Endurance/ Fun ride
WorkoutDescription: The duration the goal today. Road or MTB, just getting that TIME in on the bike. Not too fussed about HR today, the time in the saddle is where the benefit is today. 3hrs would be great, if can go longer. Go for it!
AthleteComments: *17/04/2022 Matthew Roberts: That’s what it looks like when I completely stuff up nutrition and pacing. Semi-bonk half way through. I’m still completely wrecked the next day.* *18/04/2022 Matthew Roberts: I've checked the numbers, I was pulling 157bpm in the first hour and a half.  That was "race pace" two months ago - the limit of what I could do over 90 mins.  So no surprise I blew up.  I forgot to pack snacks (too long since I did a long ride) and when I hit the servo at Prestons I was ahead of my PR for the M7.  I can't resist the chance at a PR so I didn't stop for food.  Bad idea.  Next available stop is over 30 mins away so I crawl into Eastern Creek to get coke and choccie milk. Just kept me above completely bonking and struggled home.  I turned off the live segments on my wahoo since its always getting me in trouble, but I knew the halfway time for that ride so it didn't help :) The real surprise is that my legs were not telling me I was going too hard in the first half - felt strong until it all evaporated over a 10 minute period.* *18/04/2022 Matthew Roberts: FYI: commuting on wed/thur/fri this week* *18/04/2022 Justin Morris: Thats promising apart from the nutrition approach. Nutrition is number 1 thing to prepare for on any ride further than 45min. ALWAYS pack food, some short acting carb (lollies/ anything high sugar base) and a slower release carb (oats museli bar). Realistically at a firm pace should be topping up carbs every 60min, so that was the big factor in the bonk today. Especially backing up after yesty. But good to know you were holding highest ever pace on way up, that is evidence your form is coming up if you are holding a race pace with your sensations suggesting you are riding easy. Some of these rides, good to put the garmin in the pocket and just pedal gauging nothing but sensations.*

Title: Road bike- Bobbo commute

If you can leave earlier: Ride easy to Bobbo: On climb: 9/10 pace so 160+bpm until toll booth, then after toll booth: 10/10 from toll booth to the crest of the hill by the school. Then easy rest of the way into Mac. If way home is easier to get bobbo in; same approach on Bobbo west but after kalkari it's 10RPE for 40s out of saddle.
CoachComments: This is what helps lift your perspective of what is hard and of course your anaerobic capacity. Generally the topography tends to dictate effort, this is trying to override the topography with your psychology/ motivation. The top IS NOT the top. I will keep hammering :-).

Title: Home Trainer 1 Leg Session !
WorkoutDescription: Good one to revisit when stuck on the home trainer and prioritising active recovery. Never too late or too good to revisit the fundamentals of a smooth pedal stroke :-).This is designed to SMOOTH out your pedalling motion. It is very, very effective but also quite challenging! Set up a chair or something to prop your non working leg on next to the trainer. The main priority in this is to be SMOOTH! No stress about heart rate or power or anything else. Smooth, like you are buttering toast with peanut butter and the bottom of your foot is the knife. If you can turn you Wahoo OFF and just use it as a regular trainer would be best as I don't want you to stress about numbers per se. The 9 & 6 RPE on the workout builder are just to indicate when the 1 leg sessions are. NO power, NO HR really required The 1 minute between each 1 leg sector allows a bit of recovery (clip both legs back in for this 1 min) Then that 10min working session toward the end both legs in and I want you to note if you feel any different sensations in your pedal stroke after doing the 1 leggers Another KEY building block for a cyclist, this is FORM and STYLE on the bike - this is what allows you to push more power through the pedals when we dial this in.
CoachComments: This will give you 4x1 min Left leg and 4x 1min Right leg. Nice and even! Get familiar with doing this style of work as I'll be asking you to do more of it ;-).

Title: Pre Race breathing tips
WorkoutDescription: 4 seconds: breathe in through nose 4 seconds: hold breath 4 seconds: long breath out through mouth
CoachComments: The idea of this is it lowers your heart rate; especially important in any scenario that is anxiety enducing, nerve wracking. Enables more clarity of thought and free's up more calories to be used as power to the pedals rather than worry calories..

Title: 15s of fury!
WorkoutDescription: This is the first of this kind of work we have done and it is worth giving a crack now some races on the radar. Also be interesting to see how your body reacts to this kind of work. So rather than the strength and endurance work we have been doing this is just hammering the pedals for a short intense period of time. 15s efforts, Spend the whole 15s out of the saddle and just hammering as hard as you can. Recovery is short between efforts which helps train the HR to drop more after a hard effort which is something that did not happen at yarramundi. Work this into longer ride 2hours or so.. Could work it into your commute. Focus on the sensation of effort! NOT any numbers!

Title: 6s + 20s sharpeners
WorkoutDescription: IN RPE this week Matt, give it a good crack... Focusing on the thoughts you going to need/ use on race day, if there are some trails like OMV open I suggest heading there. Those 2 blocks can slot in at any point during this ride. The 2 sprints per effort are what counts; 6s BLAST, lift the effort to max! 54s back to tempo what you'd consider a regular race pace, then 20s BLAST full gas! then 1min easy. FEELING focus! Follow your sensations.
AthleteComments: *12/06/2022 Matthew Roberts: didn't work for three reasons: 1) had a headache when I left, but it was cleared by the second set 2) on an XC track, you can't choose when you put in effort.  I couldn't get the timing to work well.  Also, when you are trying to go MAX and a you have to slow down, then you drop from MAX.  Exactly the opposite is a problem too, trying to stay at "race pace' and some feature pushes you into way into the red 3) once I go 4 seconds at MAX, any reasonable effort keeps me there.  The lactic acid and the struggling for oxygen starts and it just won't stop unless I really drop off the intensity for a while.  So 4 secs MAX then race pace is either 4 secs "a little over race pace' then race pace or it is a minute-twenty MAX.* *13/06/2022 Justin Morris: You are right about doing efforts on an MTB track if it were HR or W data, However, RPE is just a feeling or sensation of effort. So imagining you are in a race and getting the most out of your body whatever the terrain. Saying that, I would have tried to do these mainly on the climb  not the descent. I should've written that out apologies. Alas, you hammered it around some XC trail for 90min so most important mission accomplished.* *13/06/2022 Matthew Roberts: I did do it on climbs but they were not long enough for the full set and I was never in a place I could head back down in the rest sections!*

Title: Descending gear efforts
WorkoutDescription: Turns into a strength endurance session: 10min easy warm up, increase cadence as the warm up progresses. THEN: Begin in easiest gear: 2min in that gear then 1 gear harder, 2min in that gear THEN 1 gear harder etc. etc. Do the full range in the little ring then the full range in the big ring, THEN cool down 5min. No specific structure, just gears and pedalling. Going to be a grind :-).

Title: FTP test
WorkoutDescription: Morning or evening whichever you feel more energetic in.The aim of this is to help ascertain some of the important values required from your power/HR data. This is called your 'functional threshold' test. It gives us a number that indicates how hard you can go for approximately an hour.
CoachComments: I would suggest a long, flat road with 0 traffic lights/ distractions. Pay attention to the 3 high leg speed warm up drills prior to the effort, these are important to get the mosyt out of this effort. The effort will 20mins FLAT OUT! Imagine you are doing a time trial, focus your attention, your energy, your thoughts on the effort. This will encourage you to look inside your feeling a little and help you appreicate how hard you can actually go and how much pain you can actually deal with!

Title: Home trainer 1 leg session! 2
WorkoutDescription: This is designed to SMOOTH out your pedalling motion. It is very, very effective but also quite challenging! Set up a chair or something to prop your non working leg on next to the trainer. Have a look at what I have written below. The main priority in this is to be SMOOTH! No stress about heart rate or anything else. Smooth, like you are buttering toast with peanut butter and the bottom of your foot is the knife. If you can turn you Wahoo OFF and just use it as a regular trainer would be best as I don't want you to stress about numbers per se for this.. Just being SMOOTH.. Will be really good particuarly on a reco week like this week. The ON/OFF RPE on the workout builder are just to indicate when the 1 leg sessions are. NO power, NO HR really required..
CoachComments: Will give you 5x L leg and 5x R leg.

Title: Home Trainer 1 Leg Session !
WorkoutDescription: Same as last week but with a blast afterward. Set up a chair or something to prop your non working leg on next to the trainer. The main priority in this is to be SMOOTH! No stress about heart rate or power or anything else. Smooth, like you are buttering toast with peanut butter and the bottom of your foot is the knife. If you can turn you Wahoo OFF and just use it as a regular trainer would be best as I don't want you to stress about numbers per se. The 9 & 6 RPE on the workout builder are just to indicate when the 1 leg sessions are. NO power, NO HR really required The 1 minute between each 1 leg sector allows a bit of recovery (clip both legs back in for this 1 min) Then that 10min working session toward the end both legs in and I want you to note if you feel any different sensations in your pedal stroke after doing the 1 leggers Another KEY building block for a cyclist, this is FORM and STYLE on the bike - this is what allows you to push more power through the pedals when we dial this in.
CoachComments: This will give you 4x1 min Left leg and 4x 1min Right leg. Nice and even! Get familiar with doing this style of work as I'll be asking you to do more of it ;-).

Title: Trainer- FOCUS training
WorkoutDescription: After getting the blood pumping for 10min or so, I want you to engage the mind in turning those pedals...- Do this by COUNTING EACH PEDAL STROKE! See how high of a number you can get. If your mind wanders and you lose count... Start again!! 1 rotation of the pedals= 1 count! Continue for 10mins then 5min break where mind can wander again, then 10mins ON with the counting again. The RPE denotes 'mental power' in this session as opposed to leg power..
CoachComments: The idea of this is to FOCUS 100% of your thinking power to turning the pedals. The rationale is that if your mind is not fully engaged you cannot be giving your full potential of energy to the practice. COMPLETELY PRESENT!! The counting is the most straightforward way to train the mind toward 100% focus on what you are doing.. No thinking about work, no thinking about whats for brekkie, no thinking about the future or the past- JUST turning the pedals. Somewhat like meditation!

Let me know which number you get to counting before you lose count! Start from 0 again when you lose count. 4th effort: 1 leg effort, 1min on 1min off, alternate legs!

WorkoutDescription: Ideally on the course, but otherwise just rolling on the road. When it's hot suggest against warm up on trainer- too easy to dehydrate/ overheat before race has even begun! That will be enough to get anaerobic system firing pre race.

Title: Race day - structured warmup
WorkoutDescription: Begin about 1 hour and no later than 50 minutes before race start. You need 30 minutes for this session. Try not to rush it. Scout out a good warmup location. A quiet, long road, a good hill, or even a nearby suburban block you can go round and round will all be okay. If you can access the race course, it's fine to do it there too. The race-warm-up session prepares the body for the event ahead. The intensity of the first ramp is gradually increased over a 10 minute period. Take it slowly. At about 9 minutes into the first ramp, your heart rate or power output should be at threshold - hold this for the last 60 seconds but don't go over threshold. Next, carry out a short easy recovery spin before two short threshold efforts for 1 minute. Again. Don't do all-out efforts. Threshold will feel easy if the adrenaline is pumping. That's good! If you are running late or strapped for time or if the weather is very hot, skip the last one or two threshold intervals and do a shorter cool down. Time this session so you have enough time to get to the start line without cooling down too much. I always start 1 hour to 50 mins before. Then do a quick dunny break and get to the start line 15 minutes before the gun. Any spare time, just ride close to the start and keep the legs turning over.

Title: XCO
AthleteComments: *20/11/2022 Matthew Roberts: Urg* *20/11/2022 Matthew Roberts: My worst race since I started again in 2018!  First lap was at a decent pace but it got worse every lap.  Last lap I was creeping, worried I was going to lose my lunch.  My post-mortem is that a) I was sick leading up, b) I had too much sugar and my stomach said no, c) the course had a big climb which is not my strength. I lost one water bottle at the start and only had my gatorade bottle left.  Made the bad decision not to swap it out at the end of the last lap for my spare bottle and combined with honey on my porridge fro breakfast, gatorade before race, and lollies before race - not good.  So the die is set now for my race nutrition: normal breakfast, a handfull of lollies before race, first bottle is water, second bottle (lap 3+) is isotonic.* *20/11/2022 Justin Morris: Sounds like dehydration was the main culprit here and been sick. The gatorade offers no real hydration (despite what the label might say) so it really needs to be tempered with H2O. If went straight to sports drink off the start you would have been dehydrated by the end of first lap and then the drink you did have was just making it worse. Enjoy the day off tomorrow and hopefully shakes that sickness. According to the HR data, looks like you are still fighting it.*

Title: Zone 2 with microintervals 12x40/20 x 1
WorkoutDescription: This is still a general endurance ride but with 12 of those 40s efforts to tap into the anaerobic effort before the reco week. These are good on a long hill (8-10 mins) or on a flat to undulating course. Avoid long downhills. Use your gears to get the effort right. The key is to go HARD in the 40 second intervals. This is a VO2 effort at about 8-9 RPE (ouch). The easy is at about Zone 1-2. Overall, your heart rate will creep up around threshold, but it's not a useful guide for the intervals themselves. Good luck, let me know how you go in the comments.

Title: Zone 2 with singletrack
WorkoutDescription: There is a large body of evidence demonstrating the positive physiological benefits of Zone 2 riding - which is great because it's easy. Bear in mind though that proper Zone 2 riding takes considerable focus. It's very easy to go out and do a random ride that starts too hard and finishes too easy. Watch your heart rate for this one and stick to the heart rate zone. Pedal softly uphill and keep the pressure on the pedals down the hills. Ride some singletrack in the second half of the ride. Try to keep a similar feeling of load on your HR, although it will likely drop and rise out of the channel. This is fine. Return to Zone 2 once you're back on the road/fire road.

Title: Zone 2 with a tempo kick medium
WorkoutDescription: Aerobic development rides are fundamental for endurance athletes given the enormous role that aerobic metabolism plays in training and competition.
CoachComments: This particular workout adds in some 3 minute efforts just below the lactate threshold towards the end of the ride. These late-stage efforts are designed to activate Type IIa muscle fibres, which are fast-twitch fibres that can be made more aerobically capable with training. This one isn't going to sting at all and brings heaps of benefits!

WorkoutDescription: If possible do this prior to Dirt Dash as like a warm up. More of this Z2 fun. Road bike be best for this one. You likely know the sensation of Z2 pretty good now, so just aim to hold it for the duration of the ride. HR range is there as a guide.
CoachComments: Peebles Road is a good ride for this kind of duration: https://www.strava.com/routes/19472817 Can go through Gorge instead of Berowra if want to make much shorter.

Title: 2x gorges at speed
WorkoutDescription: Can spend most of this ride at a real easy tempo as easy as you like. Permission to not worry about that Z2 goal at all. However, for Galston gorge and Berowra Waters, or Brooklyn and Bobbo. Whichever 2 climbs you choose. Those 2 climbs have to be FULL GAS. Go for PR type effort. That 8-12min effort is the target here, you will get better at appreciating how to pace yourself for this effort. For this distance it is not a full gas start that helps, it is more an 8/10 start and building into the effort. Finish the climb fully fisted but try not to stop, best to keep spinning REAL EASY.
AthleteComments: *13/01/2023 Matthew Roberts: first effort was not good.  Thought I really did well but was miles off my PB.  Got a coffee and had a go at the second - PB!* *13/01/2023 Justin Morris: The power of brew :-). Yeah, sorry mate I prob would have moved this forward a week given getting over being crook. that would have been the factor in that first effort sensations. When recovering from sickness takes a lot longer for the body to warm up. No harm in having done this and pretty impressed you could put out what you did. You'll be ready to fire next week :-).*

Title: Group ride
WorkoutDescription: La Reve or something similar. Main aim is to be with a group, increases speed and helps to decrease the anxiety associated with riding in a group.

Title: Technical repeats - skills and speed - 15 min loop
WorkoutDescription: Find a challenging section of trail, and create a loop where you can hit it over and over again (e.g. a brief downhill section with a short climb back up). Use a loop of approx 15 minutes if possible - try OMV or maybe jungo-pony club. Perform a warmup including a loop at slower speed to scope out the obstacles. Learn from each repeat and analyse where you can take a better line, stay off the brakes and change your body position to improve your speed and flow. Tip: Try to look further down the trail and spot any obstacles or changes in the trail as early as possible, while training your peripheral vision to register obstacles in the more immediate vicinity. How far ahead can you look? Goal here is to make each lap quicker than the previous, should be able to get 4 of them in.

Title: Easy/ Active recovery spin- 1 hand focus
WorkoutDescription: Bit of practice for next Wednesday. If you can find a steady gradient hill of a few minutes in length try 20s alternating between 1 handed left hand and 1 handed right hand. Focussing on keeping the bike straight whilst 1 handed, should feel it in the oblique stabilising muscles too.
AthleteComments: *16/01/2023 Matthew Roberts: My quads are still sore. I can ride just fine but I figured I'm best keeping it to zone 1.  I don't feel cooked or tired. Just got soreness in quads.* *19/01/2023 Justin Morris: Zone 1 good for this ride mate. Especially if the quads are still sore, good indication to spin the legs easy in easy gears only.*

Title: Thursday Strength
WorkoutDescription: 5/6 min for this week. Slow RPM, flat foot on the downstroke, hands in drops during the low RPM effort. Could use Bobbo especially the section after you turn left where it gets steeper (Turra side) Or could also use the Quarter sessions loop, even if it is a little short than 5/6 min still do just 4.

Title: Easy/ Active recovery spin- 1 hand focus
WorkoutDescription: Bit of practice for Wednesday. If you can find a steady gradient hill of a few minutes in length try 20s alternating between 1 handed left hand and 1 handed right hand. Focussing on keeping the bike straight whilst 1 handed, should feel it in the oblique stabilising muscles too.

Title: Strength Endurance- 1 hand
WorkoutDescription: You could do this on Bobbo again. Steady gradient. HARD gear and low cadence, this is building up your strength endurance which will start to filter in through Feb. It is the next level after endurance.. So ability of the muscles to keep dumping out big power for extended periods of time. Low cadence is the key on these, know you don't have the cadence meter, but you know the feeling now. HARD gear just slower revolutions. During those 6min efforts. Alternate hand on the bar and hand behind back. So 1 hand behind back and 1 hand on bar for 30s then swap hands for the whole 6min. This switches on the core as well as the leg muscles.

Title: Commute or MTB ride
WorkoutDescription: Through Penno park if can commute. After the strength endurance yesterday it is best to follow up with higher cadence/ lower power riding. Hence, MTB a great option today, stay in the easier ratios and try to avoid steep climbs, tomac climb will obviously be an exception as required.

Title: Group ride + extra
WorkoutDescription: Can move this around as you need. I know the big rides take a bit out of you and some time to recover, hence will put this before a reco week/ after a few days off. Just 1 of these type rides per month should suffice to ensure you are good to make the full day on march 4. Head for 5 hrs, anymore is a bonus!

Title: Reco Ride on MTB
WorkoutDescription: Recovery rides on mtb have a number of benefits over reco on road: -easier gears to spin with. -Being within more dense tree's/nature leads to greater oxygen uptake to assist recovery or so the old wives tale suggests.
